  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Offering to the Venerable Monk Uija
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lee, an official of the royal court, humbly present this offering of tea and fruit to the spirit of the Venerable Monk Uija.

    Consider the spirit: heir to the lineage of Buddha's Slope, successor to the teachings of Youxi. A perfect vessel of the dharma, abundant and complete. His practice was lofty, his way deep and unfathomable. Beyond his spiritual mastery, his brush wielded words like a dragon's fury and tiger's might—sweeping across paper with wind's chill and rain's mist. His vision was broad and open, touching all things with clarity.

    In those early days we first met, we lingered in leisurely conversation. Upon Zeng Mountain's bank we came and went, asking of the Way, speaking of Emptiness. What was this Way we sought? It was Emptiness, Illusory Form, and the Middle Way combined. Through these sacred words, you illuminated my blindness; by your grace alone did you open these deaf ears and clouded eyes.

    How well I remember: bamboo windows in night rain, the clear wind through the pine hall, lamplight circling the go board while we forgot the sun's descent. Or composing verses together, polishing each word between us. You poured wine until I drowned in its warmth, a hundred cups deep. You let me rest upon your lap while I slept, my breath rising like a rainbow. We cast aside all formality, laid bare our very hearts.

    Together we wandered to National Clarity monastery—vermillion maples framing the banks. Side by side we rode to Sweet Dew Temple where green waters churned and heaved. Upon the mountain peak we shared the wine cup, sipping and savoring, chanting and singing—such joy it was, suffused with harmony.

    Alas! In human life, gathering and scattering—parting comes easy, meeting comes hard. Once separated, we drifted like tumbleweeds. When I went south to serve, you withdrew to the old peaks. When you returned to the western temple, I journeyed east. Our comings and goings grew misaligned as spring swallows and autumn geese. Then suddenly we met, only to part again in haste. Those old joys we could not reclaim. And now this news of your passing strikes me like thunder.

    Water flows and does not return. Clouds drift and leave no trace. The pillar of the dharma has broken—how shall students find their way? In the realm of the Way, life and death are one; why then does my heart grieve so? You could not linger in this dusty world. Surely you have ascended to the Palace of Tusita Heaven. How I wish to follow, to meet you there and share one last laugh together.

    I offer this tea leaf, tender as new growth, a humble token of my unending sorrow.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Buddha's Slope and Youxi refer to the lineages of Chan Buddhist teaching, indicating Monk Uija's position within an established spiritual tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: Emptiness, Illusory Form, and the Middle Way are core Buddhist philosophical concepts representing the threefold truth.
  - key: ''
    value: National Clarity monastery and Sweet Dew Temple are actual Buddhist temples, likely in China, where the author and monk spent time together.
  - key: ''
    value: The Palace of Tusita Heaven is where Bodhisattvas abide before becoming Buddhas—a symbol of spiritual ascension.
  - key: ''
    value: The tea leaf offering parallels the tea and fruit mentioned at the beginning, completing a ritual gesture of remembrance.
